---
import SidebarCard from '../components/SidebarCard.astro';
import ClassicShell from '../layouts/ClassicShell.astro';
import { SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL, SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_KEYWORDS, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<ClassicShell
	title={`${SITE_TITLE} | About`}
	description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}
	pageTitle="About AI Prompt Gear"
	pageIntro="AI Prompt Gear is being built as an English-language reference brand for operators, consultants, and software buyers who need AI content that stays useful after the trend cycle passes."
	introLabel="About"
	keywords={[...SITE_KEYWORDS, 'about AI Prompt Gear']}
	breadcrumbs={[
		{ name: 'Home', path: '/' },
		{ name: 'About', path: '/about/' },
	]}
>
	<Fragment slot="left-rail">
		<SidebarCard title="Audience" eyebrow="Who It Helps">
			<ul>
				<li>Operators building repeatable AI workflows</li>
				<li>Teams comparing copilots, assistants, and model tooling</li>
				<li>Readers who value reusable systems over generic AI commentary</li>
			</ul>
		</SidebarCard>

		<SidebarCard title="Editorial Bias" eyebrow="What We Favor">
			<p>
				We favor durable frameworks, clean information architecture, and pages that remain useful long
				enough to become meaningful assets.
			</p>
		</SidebarCard>
	</Fragment>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Editorial Thesis</p>
				<h2>Prompt content should behave like infrastructure</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			Instead of chasing shallow updates, this site is structured around prompt systems, agent
			workflows, and tool evaluation pages that can rank, convert, and remain useful for a long time.
			The three-column layout supports that by keeping navigation, reading flow, and future commercial
			surfaces clearly separated.
		</p>
	</section>

	<div class="detail-grid">
		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">SEO Logic</p>
			<h3>Long-tail, system-oriented queries</h3>
			<p>
				The strongest pages will target repeatable jobs to be done: writing workflows, research
				processes, prompt libraries, and buyer comparison queries with commercial intent.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Trust</p>
			<h3>Clarity beats volume</h3>
			<p>
				The brand goal is to look and feel deliberate, not crowded. Reserved sponsor placements exist, but
				user value and readability come first so the site can mature without feeling extractive.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Growth Path</p>
			<h3>Libraries, playbooks, comparisons</h3>
			<p>
				Those three content shapes create a natural moat, stronger internal linking, and cleaner paths
				for future revenue from software sponsors, premium assets, and direct partnerships.
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Planning Surface</p>
				<h2>The long-term framework is visible inside the site</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			The <a href="/topics/">topic map</a> defines the clusters worth building, while the
			<a href="/methodology/"> methodology page</a> explains how the archive should stay useful and
			trustworthy as commercially important pages grow.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Reach Out</p>
				<h2>Editorial notes and future partnerships</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			For corrections, topic ideas, or future sponsor conversations, email <a href={`mailto:${SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>.
			The infrastructure is already being prepared for a cleaner long-term business, but the current priority is building a high-quality editorial base first.
		</p>
	</section>
</ClassicShell>
